  <content>
    <title>Message Queue Patterns and Implementation</title>

    <summary>Asynchronous message passing between services using brokers (RabbitMQ, Redis Streams, Celery, SQS) with mandatory idempotent consumers, dead-letter queues (DLQ) with alerts, manual acknowledgment, and explicit retry policies. Every consumer must implement an idempotency key check before processing; every queue must have a paired DLQ with max-receive-count 3-5.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Distributed async processing fails silently when consumers are not idempotent and DLQs are absent. "At-least-once" delivery is the practical guarantee of every broker; without idempotency, duplicate messages corrupt data. Without DLQ and alert, poison messages block queues indefinitely. The outbox pattern prevents message loss when publishing inside DB transactions.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Decoupling producer and consumer services with different throughput or availability profiles.</item>
        <item>Background work: emails, image processing, LLM calls, webhook fan-out.</item>
        <item>Load leveling during traffic spikes.</item>
        <item>Event-driven architectures: one publish to multiple independent subscribers.</item>
        <item>Reliable delivery with retry + dead-letter for at-least-once processing.</item>
        <item>Decoupling producer and consumer services with very different throughput or availability profiles.</item>
        <item>Background work: emails, image/video processing, PDF generation, LLM calls, webhook fan-out.</item>
        <item>Load leveling during traffic spikes (sign-ups, cron job storms, marketing pushes).</item>
        <item>Event-driven architectures: order placed to invoice + shipping + analytics consumers.</item>
        <item>Fan-out / pub-sub: one publish hits many independent subscribers.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Hard real-time request/response (chat, payment confirmation in user UI) — use sync HTTP/RPC.</item>
        <item>Single-process workers — asyncio.Queue or goroutines are simpler.</item>
        <item>Multi-step transactional flows where ordering and exactly-once matter — use a workflow engine (Temporal, Airflow).</item>
        <item>Streaming analytics with windowing — use Kafka + Flink/ksqlDB.</item>
        <item>Storing large blobs — queues are for references; put bytes in S3/object storage.</item>
        <item>Coordination of multi-step transactional flows where ordering and exactly-once matter — use a workflow engine (Temporal, Airflow, Prefect) instead.</item>
        <item>Streaming analytics with windowing — use Kafka + Flink/ksqlDB, not a queue.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="core-patterns">
      <p>Fundamental messaging patterns for distributed systems.</p>

      <section name="work-queue">
        <p>One producer, one consumer group. Each message processed by exactly one consumer. Best for background jobs: email, image processing, report generation.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="publish-subscribe">
        <p>One producer, multiple independent consumer groups. Each group receives every message. Best for event-driven fan-out: order-placed to invoice + shipping + analytics.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="dead-letter-queue">
        <p>Messages that exceed max-receive-count are routed to the DLQ instead of being re-queued infinitely. DLQ must have an alert on depth greater than 0 and a replay process.</p>

        <rule>
          <statement>Every queue must have a paired DLQ with max-receive-count 3-5. Add an alert when DLQ depth exceeds 0. Without a DLQ, failed messages retry until they block the queue or are silently discarded.</statement>
          <rationale>Poison messages block FIFO queues indefinitely when there is no DLQ. Without an alert, the DLQ becomes a silent black hole where failed messages accumulate unnoticed.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="broker-selection">
      <p>Choosing a message broker by guarantee and operational cost.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pick the broker by the weakest guarantee you can accept: Redis Streams for lightweight at-least-once with consumer groups; RabbitMQ for flexible routing, DLX, and TTL; SQS for fully managed with built-in DLQ; Kafka only when ordered replay across multiple consumer groups is critical.</statement>
        <rationale>Kafka adds significant operational overhead (partition rebalancing, KRaft/ZooKeeper management). For most solo SaaS workloads, Redis Streams or RabbitMQ provide sufficient guarantees at lower operational cost.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Redis Streams / Valkey: lightweight, consumer groups, ack model. Already running on faion-net.</item>
        <item>RabbitMQ: mature, DLX + TTL patterns, flexible routing (direct/topic/fanout/headers).</item>
        <item>AWS SQS: fully managed, Standard (at-least-once) or FIFO (exactly-once ordered), built-in DLQ.</item>
        <item>Celery (broker: Redis/RabbitMQ): Python task queue with chains, groups, chords, beat scheduler.</item>
        <item>Kafka: pick only when ordered replay across N independent consumer groups is the core requirement.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="rabbitmq-implementation">
      <p>RabbitMQ producer and consumer patterns with delivery guarantees.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set delivery_mode=2 (persistent) for all durable queue messages. Set basic_qos(prefetch_count=10) to prevent one worker hogging all messages. Use manual ack (auto_ack=False) with ack after successful processing.</statement>
        <rationale>Non-persistent messages survive only in memory; a broker restart loses them. High prefetch without manual ack means one slow consumer starves others. Auto-ack before processing causes message loss on consumer crash mid-handler.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/rabbitmq-client.py">RabbitMQ producer + consumer with DLQ and persistent delivery</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="celery-implementation">
      <p>Python Celery task queue configuration and best practices.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set task_acks_late=True and task_reject_on_worker_lost=True in Celery config. Set worker_prefetch_multiplier=1 for slow handlers. Without task_acks_late, a message is acked when the worker receives it, not when processing completes; a crash loses the task.</statement>
        <rationale>Default Celery acks on receipt. A worker that crashes mid-task has already acked; the task is lost. task_acks_late defers ack to completion, enabling safe replay on crash.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use transaction.on_commit() (Django) or an outbox pattern when calling apply_async() from inside a DB transaction. A commit that follows apply_async() but before the DB commit means consumers race the writer.</statement>
        <rationale>If apply_async() is called inside a transaction that later rolls back, the task still runs and processes data that was never committed. Outbox pattern publishes the task as part of the DB commit.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Celery task with retry backoff and failure handler">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from celery import Celery, Task

app = Celery('tasks', broker='redis://localhost:6379/0',
             backend='redis://localhost:6379/1')

app.conf.update(
    task_serializer='json',
    accept_content=['json'],
    task_acks_late=True,
    task_reject_on_worker_lost=True,
    worker_prefetch_multiplier=1,
)

class BaseTask(Task):
    autoretry_for = (Exception,)
    retry_backoff = True
    retry_backoff_max = 600
    retry_jitter = True
    max_retries = 5

@app.task(base=BaseTask, bind=True)
def process_order(self, order_id: str):
    order = get_order(order_id)
    charge_payment(order)
    send_confirmation(order)
    return {"status": "completed", "order_id": order_id}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="idempotency-requirement">
      <p>Essential pattern for safe at-least-once delivery semantics.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Every message consumer must implement idempotency: check a processed-messages table for the idempotency key before processing. Use INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING to claim the key atomically. Design for at-least-once delivery and rely on the idempotency check, not broker guarantees, for exactly-once semantics.</statement>
        <rationale>"Exactly once" is a marketing claim. Every broker delivers at-least-once under failure conditions. Idempotent consumers produce correct results regardless of delivery count.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="scripts/idempotent-handler.py">DB-backed idempotency key claim with ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Known failure modes and operational limitations.</p>
      <list>
        <item>"Exactly once" is a marketing promise; in practice plan for at-least-once and design idempotent consumers.</item>
        <item>DLQ without an alerting + replay process becomes a black hole.</item>
        <item>Unbounded retries on a poison message stop the queue for everyone (head-of-line blocking on FIFO queues).</item>
        <item>Queues do not enforce ordering across partitions/shards; if you need global order, throughput is capped at one consumer.</item>
        <item>RabbitMQ TTL+DLX patterns silently lose messages if exchange/queue not declared exactly right.</item>
        <item>Redis Streams are great until memory pressure causes maxlen to trim unread messages.</item>
        <item>Celery + Redis broker has no transactional guarantees for apply_async from inside a DB transaction — use transaction.on_commit().</item>
        <item>SQS: 256 KB hard message limit; visibility timeout misconfig causes duplicate processing.</item>
        <item>Kafka adds operational cost (Zookeeper/KRaft, ZK upgrades, partition rebalancing); overkill for solo SaaS.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A planner subagent picks the broker (RabbitMQ vs Redis Streams vs Celery vs SQS vs Kafka) based on guarantees needed (at-least-once / ordering / fan-out / TTL / size). An implementer subagent writes producer + consumer + DLQ wiring + retry policy. A reliability subagent generates idempotency tests (replay same message N times) and chaos tests (kill consumer mid-process, restart, verify no duplicate effect). A monitoring subagent provisions queue-depth + age-of-oldest-message dashboards + alerts.</p>

      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <p>Subagents for message queue reliability and operations.</p>
        <list>
          <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — runs spec to code to idempotency-tests to review.</item>
          <item>A user-defined chaos-runner (model: haiku) — simulates consumer crash mid-handler, verifies replay safety.</item>
          <item>A user-defined idempotency-auditor (model: sonnet) — reads handler code, flags non-idempotent operations (raw INSERTs, non-conditional emails, charges without idempotency key).</item>
          <item>password-scrubber-agent — sweep messages and tests for embedded credentials.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="prompt-patterns">
        <p>Reusable LLM prompt patterns for message queue tasks.</p>

        <prompt purpose="broker-selection"><![CDATA[
Read `message-queues/README.md`. Given workload `<X>` (rate, payload size, ordering, retry semantics), pick a broker and justify in 5 bullets. Output a YAML config: queue names, DLQ name, max receive count, TTL, prefetch.
]]></prompt>

        <prompt purpose="implement-rabbitmq"><![CDATA[
Implement RabbitMQ producer + consumer for `orders` with DLQ, persistent delivery, prefetch=10, manual ack. Add a unit test that proves replaying the same message twice causes exactly one DB row. Use the `idempotency_key` column.
]]></prompt>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>CLI tools for message queue operations and inspection.</p>
      <list>
        <item>rabbitmqadmin — Declare queues/exchanges, publish, consume from CLI. Bundled with RabbitMQ.</item>
        <item>redis-cli / valkey-cli — XADD, XREADGROUP, XPENDING for Streams ops. Bundled.</item>
        <item>awscli (aws sqs) — Send/receive/inspect SQS queues. Install: pip install awscli</item>
        <item>kcat (former kafkacat) — Kafka producer/consumer/inspector. https://github.com/edenhill/kcat</item>
        <item>kaf — Friendlier Kafka CLI. https://github.com/birdayz/kaf</item>
        <item>celery CLI — celery -A app inspect active / purge / events. Install: pip install celery</item>
        <item>flower — Celery monitoring dashboard. Install: pip install flower</item>
        <item>pulsar-admin — Pulsar topic ops. Bundled.</item>
        <item>nats CLI — NATS / JetStream ops. https://docs.nats.io/using-nats/nats-tools/nats_cli</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services">
      <p>Message broker services and applications.</p>
      <list>
        <item>RabbitMQ (OSS) — Mature; classic, quorum, streams queues; great DLX/TTL. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Redis Streams / Valkey (OSS) — Lightweight, consumer groups, ack model. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>AWS SQS (SaaS) — Standard + FIFO; built-in DLQ; trivial to scale. Agent-friendly via boto3, IaC.</item>
        <item>AWS SNS + SQS fan-out (SaaS) — Cheap pub-sub; combine with SQS for durable subscribers. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Google Pub/Sub (SaaS) — At-least-once, dead-letter topics, filters. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Kafka / Redpanda (OSS / SaaS) — Heavy; pick when ordering + replay across consumers is critical. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Pulsar (OSS / SaaS) — Tiered storage; multi-tenant; geo-replication. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>NATS / JetStream (OSS) — Low-latency, simple ops; good for edge / IoT. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Celery broker: Redis/RabbitMQ (OSS) — Python task queue; chains/groups/chords. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Sidekiq (OSS / SaaS) — Ruby/Rails ecosystem; Redis-backed. Partially agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>RQ / Dramatiq / Arq (OSS) — Lighter Python alternatives to Celery. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Inngest / Trigger.dev (SaaS) — TS-native event-driven workflows; great for solo. Agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Temporal (OSS / SaaS) — Workflow engine, not a queue — pick when you need state machines. Agent-friendly.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="idempotency-skeleton">
      <p>Idempotent-handler skeleton an agent should reuse in any consumer callback.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Idempotent consumer handler">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# idempotent_handler.py
import hashlib
from contextlib import contextmanager

def message_idempotency_key(msg: dict) -> str:
    # Prefer producer-supplied id; fall back to deterministic hash.
    if mid := msg.get("idempotency_key"):
        return mid
    body = repr(sorted(msg.items())).encode()
    return hashlib.sha256(body).hexdigest()

@contextmanager
def claim_once(db, key: str):
    # Postgres example: UNIQUE(idempotency_key) on processed_messages.
    inserted = db.execute(
        "INSERT INTO processed_messages(key) VALUES (%s) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING RETURNING 1",
        (key,),
    ).fetchone()
    if not inserted:
        yield False  # duplicate, skip
        return
    try:
        yield True
        db.commit()
    except Exception:
        db.rollback()
        # row stays unless caller deletes — choose: delete on failure for retry, keep for poison-stop
        db.execute("DELETE FROM processed_messages WHERE key = %s", (key,))
        db.commit()
        raise

# Usage inside consumer callback:
def handler(msg, db):
    key = message_idempotency_key(msg)
    with claim_once(db, key) as fresh:
        if not fresh:
            return  # silently ack
        do_work(msg, db)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Operational best practices for message queue usage.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Make every consumer idempotent (DB unique key, ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING, conditional updates with version/updated_at).</item>
        <item>Always wire a DLQ with max_receive_count (3-5). Add an alert when DLQ is greater than 0.</item>
        <item>Set prefetch_count (RabbitMQ) / worker_prefetch_multiplier=1 (Celery) for slow handlers; otherwise one worker hogs messages.</item>
        <item>Use manual ack + ack-after-success; never auto_ack for anything important.</item>
        <item>Persist messages (delivery_mode=2) for durable queues; mirror or use quorum queues for HA.</item>
        <item>Include correlation_id and causation_id headers for tracing through fan-out trees.</item>
        <item>Use transaction.on_commit() (Django) / outbox pattern when enqueuing from inside DB transactions, otherwise consumers race the writer.</item>
        <item>Keep payloads small (less than 10 KB ideal, less than 100 KB hard limit, less than 256 KB SQS limit). Put blobs in S3, send the URL.</item>
        <item>Set MessageRetentionPeriod on DLQs to 14+ days so you have time to triage.</item>
        <item>For Kafka: pick key deliberately — wrong key = wrong partition = lost ordering guarantees.</item>
        <item>Prefer producer-supplied idempotency keys (UUIDv7 tied to a domain action) over content hashes.</item>
        <item>Add jitter to retry backoff to avoid thundering herds on transient failures.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common mistakes AI agents make with message queue implementations.</p>
      <list>
        <item>LLMs paste the README's auto_ack=False example then forget to actually basic_ack in the success path; messages get re-delivered on prefetch refill.</item>
        <item>Agents emit consumers without idempotency. Force the idempotency_key table + ON CONFLICT in every plan.</item>
        <item>DLQ wiring with RabbitMQ dead-letter-exchange/dead-letter-routing-key: agents declare queues with mismatched arguments and silently get a different queue. Always test by publishing a known-bad message and checking the DLQ.</item>
        <item>Celery task_acks_late=True is required for safe replay but agents skip it because the default is False.</item>
        <item>For AWS SQS, agents forget visibility timeout greater than p99 handler runtime causes message processed twice in parallel.</item>
        <item>Redis Streams XCLAIM for stuck-consumer recovery is omitted by default; without it, crashed consumers block messages forever.</item>
        <item>Agents fan-out via app code (for sub in subs: queue.publish(...)) instead of using exchange/topic — this loses durability if the publisher crashes mid-loop.</item>
        <item>Outbox pattern is rarely emitted by default; LLMs publish from inside the DB transaction and you lose messages if the broker is briefly down.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: any change to retry counts, visibility timeout, or DLQ wiring on production-payment / production-email queues must be human-approved.</item>
        <item>Watch for log-spam: agents log every consumed message at INFO; in production, sample or move to DEBUG.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <p>Common failure modes in message queue usage.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Consumer without idempotency: assumes each message is delivered exactly once.</description>
        <reason>Every broker delivers at-least-once under network failure, consumer crash, or rebalancing. Without idempotency, duplicate messages produce duplicate DB rows, double-charged payments, or double-sent emails.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using auto_ack=True (RabbitMQ) or acknowledging before processing.</description>
        <reason>Auto-ack removes the message from the queue before the handler runs. A crash mid-handler means the message is permanently lost. Use manual ack after successful processing.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Celery without task_acks_late=True.</description>
        <reason>Default acks on receipt. A worker crash after receipt but before completion silently drops the task. task_acks_late defers ack to completion, enabling safe replay.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Calling Celery apply_async() inside a DB transaction before the commit.</description>
        <reason>The task fires immediately. If the transaction rolls back after the task fires, the consumer processes data that never existed. Use transaction.on_commit() or the outbox pattern.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>SQS visibility timeout shorter than the p99 handler runtime.</description>
        <reason>If processing takes longer than the visibility timeout, SQS makes the message visible again while the first consumer is still processing it. Two consumers process the same message in parallel, requiring idempotency to prevent double effects.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>RabbitMQ DLX/DLQ declared with mismatched arguments on different broker restarts.</description>
        <reason>RabbitMQ queue arguments are immutable after declaration. A mismatch between the arguments in code and those on the broker produces a passive-declare error, silently routing to a different queue or failing to declare DLQ routing. Always test by publishing a known-bad message and checking the DLQ.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Fan-out via app code (for sub in subs: queue.publish(...)) instead of exchange/topic routing.</description>
        <reason>If the publisher crashes mid-loop, some subscribers receive the message and others do not. Exchange-based fan-out is atomic from the broker's perspective.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

